&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br>
What does everyone think about this class in a dungeon? I understand that often pets in dungeons = bad train = dead party. So, what do you think? Will this character be in dire straits in dungeon situations?<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
Part of it is skill in pet control, and also having some form of self invis to kill a pet if it does get excessive agro outside of the range of a /pet get lost.  The other factor is the con of the pet.  In most cases, a nec pet is around 8 or more levels lower than the caster so this can cause greens that would not agro on the pet-master to agro on the pet and has the potential to cause a real mess.<br>
<br>
I think the mages, necs and SKs (as well druids, chanters and shaman who have familiarized themsleves with pet commands and behavior) that play a beastmaster will have a fairly good grasp of the possible problems and be able to mitigate it to a large degree, but for anyone who has not played a pet capable class before, yes, there will be a steep and painfull learning curve when it comes to pet control and dungeons.<br>
<br>
Jabartik <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ueqjetx.showPublicProfile?language=EN>EQ JetX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Junior Member</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#ffffff>(8/21/01 3:03:49 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Beastlord = pet, pet = master</span><hr size=1> So far this sounds like a class that can solo quite a bit without a pet, has some weak heals, slows, haste, and is part warrior. Pet's Biatch? Maybe at lower lvls, but not too sure what to see. I also wonder if they can do things like dual wield, double attack, and what weapons they get to use. <p>Jet Black<BR>
